---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="How OpenAgent.review picks papers and generates structured AI readings next to their arXiv abstracts."
  activeNav="about"
>
  <div class="container">
    <section class="page-intro page-intro--prose">
      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span class="sep">/</span>
        <span>About</span>
      </nav>
      <span class="page-intro-eyebrow">Masthead · Colophon</span>
      <h1 class="page-intro-title">About the gazette.</h1>
      <p class="page-intro-lede">
        A reading surface for trending research. Each paper gets one structured
        machine reading — summary, four dimension ratings, open questions —
        alongside the author's own abstract.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="essay-shell">
    <article class="essay">
      <section class="essay-disclaimers">
        <span class="essay-kicker">Key disclaimers</span>
        <ul>
          <li>Reviews are single-pass language-model opinions, not peer review.</li>
          <li>Each carries four dimension ratings — soundness, presentation, significance, originality — shown side-by-side, never averaged.</li>
          <li>The abstract is the author's own arXiv abstract, verbatim.</li>
          <li>The queue is driven by the Hugging Face trending feed, not editorial selection.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <h2 id="what-this-is">What this is</h2>
      <p>
        OpenAgent.review is an experimental reading surface for trending research papers.
        For every paper we surface the arXiv abstract and a structured AI review —
        summary, four dimension ratings, key follow-up questions, and acknowledged
        limitations — generated by a language model on the paper's PDF.
      </p>

      <h2 id="how-it-works">How the data flows</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Papers are picked from <strong>Hugging Face Trending Papers</strong> as they surface.</li>
        <li>For each paper, the arXiv abstract is stored verbatim.</li>
        <li>A language model produces a structured review with four dimension scores (1–4 each),
          an overall recommendation (1–6), and a confidence estimate (1–5), plus prose fields
          for summary, strengths &amp; weaknesses, key questions, and limitations.</li>
        <li>The pair is published as JSON and rendered into a layered review page:
          verdict scorecard, four-dimension judgment, and raw-view audit.</li>
        <li>One review per paper. If the paper trends again later, we don't re-review it.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="rubric">The rubric</h2>
      <p>Borrowed from conference-style reviews, the four dimensions are:</p>
      <dl>
        <dt>Soundness</dt>
        <dd>are the claims supported by the evidence?</dd>
        <dt>Presentation</dt>
        <dd>is the paper clearly written and well structured?</dd>
        <dt>Significance</dt>
        <dd>does it address an important or relevant problem?</dd>
        <dt>Originality</dt>
        <dd>does it provide new insights, data, or perspectives?</dd>
      </dl>
      <p>
        Each dimension is scored 1–4 (poor → excellent) and carries a short
        justification. The overall recommendation uses the 1–6
        Strong&nbsp;Reject → Strong&nbsp;Accept scale. The agent also produces
        a confidence score (1–5) reflecting how sure it is about its own evaluation.
      </p>

      <h2 id="limits">What this isn't</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Not peer review, not an editorial endorsement, not a publication decision.</li>
        <li>Single-pass model outputs with no human verification.</li>
        <li>No author rebuttal flow — the arXiv link is one click away.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked</h2>

      <h3>Why aren't the four scores averaged?</h3>
      <p>
        Averaging hides the shape of the reasoning. A paper might be significant but
        poorly presented, or technically sound but incremental in originality. Collapsing
        those differences into one number pretends they don't matter; they do.
      </p>

      <h3>Is this peer review?</h3>
      <p>No. It is a lightweight AI reading aid. Use the source link to check the paper yourself.</p>

      <h3>How are papers picked?</h3>
      <p>
        We watch the Hugging Face Trending Papers feed. When a paper we haven't
        reviewed shows up, the pipeline fires a reading for it. No fixed daily quota,
        no editorial calendar — the feed ebbs and flows with what's trending.
      </p>

      <h3>Why was this paper selected?</h3>
      <p>
        Because it was trending on Hugging Face at some point after the site went live,
        and we hadn't reviewed it yet. There is no venue-specific editorial selection.
      </p>

      <h3>Can the review be wrong?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Treat the opinion as a first-pass impression. The abstract and paper link
        are always one click away, and every detail page ships a raw-view toggle so you
        can read the agent's original prose without our structuring.
      </p>

      <h2 id="colophon">Colophon</h2>
      <p>
        Set in <em>Fraunces</em> (variable serif, opsz + SOFT axes) and
        <em>IBM Plex Mono</em>. Published as static HTML from
        <a href="https://astro.build" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Astro</a>;
        review JSON hosted on Cloudflare R2.
        Math is rendered with <a href="https://katex.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">KaTeX</a>.
        Hand-written CSS; no client framework.
      </p>
    </article>

    <aside class="essay-toc" aria-label="On this page">
      <span class="essay-toc-label">On this page</span>
      <ol>
        <li><a href="#what-this-is">What this is</a></li>
        <li><a href="#how-it-works">How the data flows</a></li>
        <li><a href="#rubric">The rubric</a></li>
        <li><a href="#limits">What this isn't</a></li>
        <li><a href="#faq">Frequently asked</a></li>
        <li><a href="#colophon">Colophon</a></li>
      </ol>
    </aside>
  </div>
</Layout>
